    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1941-07-01T08:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1941-07-01T08:00:00-05:00" n="819"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d819">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.0011 European War 1939/12689: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Sweden</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Sterling</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Stockholm</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1941-07-01T14:00:00+01:00"
                            >July 1, 1941—2 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received 9:17 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>400. In speaking with Kollontay<note n="10" xml:id="d819fn10">Mme. Alexandra
                        Kollontay, Soviet Minister in Sweden.</note> this morning she stated that
                    there had been no change in Russian attitude toward assistance to China and she
                    mentioned that whereas Turkey, Iran and other countries had announced their
                    neutrality in Russo-German war China had proclaimed <hi rend="italic"
                        >friendly</hi> neutrality.</p>
                <p>She believed that fighting was going on as planned; Red Army strategy was a slow
                    retirement, while inflicting as great losses as possible on German troops, to
                    1939 frontiers of Russia which were strongly fortified and where a great stand
                    would be made.</p>
                <p>With regard to Soviet-Japanese relations, she told me confidentially that no
                    Russian troops had been removed from Manchurian frontier since signing of
                    Matsuoka–Molotov agreement.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Sterling</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
